Excellent international school located on campus that includes German & French Secondary schools and a German Primary & Kindergarten. School is academically strong although there is also a strong emphasis on holistic education including daily physical education and a broad range of personal development opportunities. The German school teaches primarily through English with various German streams tightly integrated into daily school life and academics options eg wholly German medium subject options. The school is supported by the German and Irish governments and the Eurocampus also receives support from the French government through the LFI (French school). The children are of a particularly international mix which reflects in the ethos of the school. Finally if considering this school and looking at Irish school league tables it‚Äôs worth noting that while the school scores highly on these tables it‚Äôs academic progression rate is somewhat under-reported due to the high rate of student progression to universities in other European states.

Good international atmosphere. German is taught at high level. Other subjects‚Äô tuition quality is not above average. If your main goal is to learn German it is a place for your kid to be.  But if you want to achieve good results in leaving cert probably you would be better off to find another school. Again if you are bringing kid to Ireland just for a couple of years school is a good choice as integration into ‚Äúproper‚Äù Irish school will be difficult for your child.

What can I say that hasn't already been said about this church? One of the most beautiful, and visited places in all of Ireland. The price of admission is very reasonable, and they have a nice gift shop near the entrance to pick up some nice items on the way out. 

This was one of my favorite places to visit in Dublin, and I'd like to visit it again. It's hard to convey the size of it in pictures, because you can easily spend a couple hours in there and not even realize where the time went. 

It's within walking distance of the Castle, so you can visit both in the same day.

I absolutely loved my time spent at St Patrick‚Äôs Cathedral.  The artwork and design of the cathedral is just breathtaking.  The organs playing in the background is very calming and I could listen to them for hours.  I highly recommend walking up the 350 steps to the top of the cathedral for the view of the city and if you have it in you for the last  approximately 46 steps to go to the very top.  Make sure to grab your headset for your guide tour at your own pace and learn the history behind st Patrick‚Äôs.

Places like this build the atmosphere of the city. Tradition, history and culture intertwine here and tell the story of Dublin and Ireland. It is a impressive place with many interesting features, starting with the architecture, through absolutely magnificent stained glass windows to the stories about what can be seen there. There are also concerts organised there and they fabulous. There's also a small garden beside for a nice outdoor break.

Fair warning there is a 6.50‚Ç¨ entrance fee, which is unheard of in all of my travels. As a Catholic it's tough to wrap my head around that this church charges to enter rather than working off of donations. That aside for the moment. 

The place is historic and beautiful and can be walked through and enjoyed in 30 minutes or less. The gift shop is in the back but still within view of the altar - kinda odd. 

Another issue besides having to pay to get in, just in case you didn't see that earlier, ;) are the bathrooms. If you identify as a man, their men's bathroom is as big as a thimble. Open the door and you have to maneuver your legs to get in and around the toilet. It's super tight and playing the game of Operation with my legs and the porcelain toilet isn't so appealing - when paying 6.50‚Ç¨ - to get in the church. :)

I moved to St Dominics in fourth year and it was without a doubt the best decision that I have ever made. It allowed me to mature and the teachers treated you like an adult as time went on. It's a school that allows each student to be different but welcome at the same time. I've always been given tremendous support through extra classes and just a shoulder to lean on. Teachers became friends in the end and they always have given 100% to the students. I can't praise the school enough, and I'm sad to have to go. I owe my results to their hard work and encouragement and will always have a good word to say about St Dominics. I would definitely recommend this school, and staff.

St.Dominics secondary school is without question one of the most inclusive, encouraging and think outside the box schools. By this I mean St.Dominics caters for the needs of all students equally, encouraging each one as an individual to achieve their goals and dreams. I feel so lucky to have had an opportunity to go to school there, I met my mentor Sr.Liz Smyth there who was at the time our leadership teacher. She has played a huge part in helping me become who I am today. The current school management,principal and staff team go the extra mile each time for the current students constantly thinking of new ways to engage the students. I am luck to have both my daughters there now. I can see the impact that St.Dominics is already having on them, helping them to become confident young women.

My daughter Emma is starting in St. Dominics this September. As a staff member as an SNA for nearly five years this term I would not consider sending Emma anywhere else. 
 The subjects are wide and varied 
 The modules are modern and created to meet each individual and the support given to each student to reach their full potential is remarkable. 
 The staff work long hours and all offer extra volunteer hours as well help in pre school clubs and after school clubs. 
 The activities ,extra curricular activities ,speakers , day trips, student exchanges, breakfast clubs, homework clubs, and group work that is created and implemented on going and as needed is all to meet the needs of the person and teaches needs and goals of personality of student. 
 St.Dominics not only has a high standard and high percentage of students reaching third level education but also uses a very holistic approach in enabling strong confident balanced and determined young ladies to leave after 6th year. With continued support. 
 The above does not touch on the actual events activities subjects and so on. 
 I myself have done most of my learning personally and academically and professionally in St.Dominics which is amazing as I was never lucky enough to be a student!!!

 Lisa Palmer.

Steeped in heritage. The North Monastery or "The Mon" as it's affectionately known, is comprised of two separate and distinct schools. 

The first section being the 'AG' where the students are thought exclusively in Irish. The AG would be the closest thing to an Irish 'Eton college' but with no fees. Hence the reason why so many of the teachers within the school had their children attend. The Alumni of the AG have traditionally reached the upper echelons of career success in the worlds of banking, politics, education and the Arts, to name but a few. 

The other section of the school is the 'Academic' section. Students attending this school were a mixed bunch. These would range from the high achievers to the outright 'gurriors' or messer's who had no more interest in the virtues of a good education than their AG fellow students would have in a career of carpet fitting. 

With such a mix of students in the Academic section, there were regular instances of bullying and the after school fight was at least twice a month near the Fair Hill school gate. Yours truly had engaged in two fights in his time but only as an act of warning off the bullies.

In my student days at the Mon (1990 - 1995), there were laughs and there were tears. As I get older I try to remember more the laughs than the tears.
You as students may not think it now, but you'll wish for a single day back there again before adult life starts, great very old famous school started by Brother Edmund Ignatius Rice
Good school

Unfortunately the scoring system jumps from poor to good, neither are suitable to De La Salle. Instead, I would say it is merely average. The school's management leaves a lot to be desired, constant intercom interuptions, regular half days/days off, badly organising time tables seemingly without logic, a useless career guidance councillor, redundant swipe-in system (as the names are then checked later on anyway) and the now infamous half a million debt. But moreso than that, numerous teachers are simply not up to, what I would consider, an acceptable standard of teaching. As I was leaving the school a number of the newer teachers were, after some research, not qualified for the subjects they were teaching, Maths was a particular casualty. And unfortunately, the vast majority of teachers in my experience fall under the category of "bad" as opposed to "good or better". Some exceptional teachers are in the school of course, Ms. Flannery, Ms.Hewison, Mr. Brosnan, Ms. McDonagh and Mr. Munroe are all what I would consider superb teachers but they are, as noted, the exception, not the rule. Far too many teachers rely simply upon reading the book and supplying notes, showing no enthusiasm or actual understanding of what they are teaching. My numerous encounters with the school management have left me with the impression that they are rude and unhelpful. After making an inquiry about renting a locker over the phone, my request was met with a bitterly sarcastic reply followed by a snapping insult. When I attempted to follow up this conversation and to actually get an answer, my existence was denied as the phone call had "not happened", that I "never contacted [them]" and it took another two weeks until a locker was acquired.

The school itself is an impressive building but unfortunately the modernisation effort has been in vain as numerous teachers are completely unable to use the interactive electronic boards. Vital facilities such as a working intercom, periodical testing for learning difficulties, assistance with regard to study methods and assistance for those with learning difficulties are either absent or a low standard. The school deserves recognition for its large amount of sporting facilities, six laboratories in total (with a seventh that was planned when I was attending the school) and its recent accomodation for those of us who require wheelchairs. The lockers are problematic, having recently been moved from a single room to being spread out over an entire two floors there is no accomodation for students with lockers on the timetable, students instead expected to use them at lunch and before/after school, rendering them useless. 

Unfortunately, the few exceptional teachers are the only real advantages the school has over other schools but as sorry as I am to say it, I don't think it is worth sending your child to the school as I'm sure there are exceptional teachers in other schools too. It simply is not worth it.

I have just completed an administration course in BIFE and thoroughly enjoyed my time there.  All the staff are extremely supportive and the course tutors go out of their way to help you.  There was great camaraderie in our class which consisted of students of all ages.  I feel fully equipped to regain employment and recommend the college to anyone who needs to update their skills.  The building itself is close to the main street and has excellent parking facilities.

I recently completed a QQI Level 5 in Medical Administration here.  Both the staff in the canteen and the teachers were outstanding.  An extremely positive experience, giving me the tools I need to go back into the workforce with confidence and knowledge.  A challenging course, but with dedicated teachers, it was a great challenge!

I have just completed the Medical Administration course in BIFE.  The class consisted of students of all ages.  The support received from the Tutors was fantastic, particularly from the course co-coordinator who went out of her way to ensure all understood what was being taught.  I updated my computer skills and learnt so much during this course from participating in all the modules that were available to us, "Communications, Work experience, Information Administration, Microsoft Office specialist  (Word, Access and Excel), Medical Terminology, Database Methods, Spreadsheets Methods, Text Production, Word Processing, Data Entry  and Audio Transcription".  As a mature student I would highly recommend this course, forget whatever fears you might have and fully participate , you will gain so much and make great friends, this course will help you find a job in the future.

Decided to go back to the restaurant with the wife under the impression that things might have improved since last time.

As we sat down I asked for the spaghetti carbonara. My wife had to return to the car to fetch her purse. A few moments after she left, the lights went out. Cries of "Alright, get him!" rang though my ears. What felt like a potato-sack was forced on my head as a loud ringing became all I could hear.

I awoke in an empty auditorium. Trying to move, I found that I couldn't, bound to an ordinary chair, like the sort we used to have in school. What felt like hours passed before I heard the door creek open. Out of my line of sight, I could not see who entered. Hearing only their footsteps as they crept behind me.

The person behind me gently brushed the back of my head. A searing pain went through me as I realized that they had just prodded a fresh wound.

I started doing all I could think to do, struggle. I rocked my chair back and forth, screaming, trying to get free. The person walked in front of me, their face obscured by darkness. They held my face in their hand and sprayed some sort of liquid into my mouth. It tasted like some sort of cleaning agent. "If you do that again, it's going to be bleach" they said in a distinctly male voice.

As they walked out of the room, I couldn't help but fear what my wife may have been going through at the same time as me. In sheer panic, I kept fighting. I had to stop after I found the rope was cutting me, and attached to my wrists at that. I couldn't risk it.

After a few thrusts, I managed to knock the chair over. Pushing myself along with my toes, I crept closer and closer to the door for about half an hour. Then two figures walked in. "They always try it, every single god damn time!". The taller of the two kicked me in the stomach, paralyzing me with pain as they propped me up again.

"What's the plan with this one?" the shorter of the two said, "Scenario 46G-631" The taller replied, "Re... Really? That's a bit much don't you thi-" "THAT... is that the boss said. Now I suggest you shut up and do your job before he sees us slacking off".

The shorter pulled out a large knife "Now don't you dare move" he told me. Holding it close to me, I feared for the worst. He moved it slowly down and began cutting the ropes. The second he was done I bolted for the door, but the taller of the two knocked me down. I could hear my nose break inside my head. It sounding like eating a pretzel.

I was reduced to a pool of blood and tears. They picked me up as I began to beg for mercy "Oh, shut up. Honestly, they always say the same things" the taller said.

They threw me into a small wooden crate, but before I could attempt to move they threw the lid on. I heard nails being driven into wood before hearing their footsteps get further and further away. Then the door slammed shut.

Resigned to my fate, I decided I should try to sleep, and hope that somebody reported me missing. I'm not sure if what happened next was a dream or not, but I remember waking up to a person wearing a surgical mask, holding a drill. They said "Damn it, he's not supposed to be awake". I passed out after that.

I awoke in the box. Sunlight was peeking through the cracks. Then a shadow took over. "Alright, get 'im outta there". Crowbars pried the crate open, I saw three men standing before me. Their faces fully uncovered, but my vision too blurry to make anything out.

I was unable to move my jaw, "Pleash, pleash, jusht lhet meh gho", "Not yet." one of them responded "First, we've gotta give you something". "Pleash don' hurt meh". "Hurt? Oh lord no. This shouldn't hurt... much". He grabbed me, I could feel the remnants of my bones scraping together.

He forced me into a chair, I couldn't move anything except my right hand. They left the room. After about an hour, they returned. "Sorry for the delay, but now we can begin". He started to grin as I prepared for an agony worse than I could imagine.

And it was worse than I could imagine... They didn't even season the pasta properly. Would rate 0 stars if possible.
Never even been here, but looks like the worst restaurant ever

UNBELIEVABLE!. They wouldn't take my order, didn't have a table for me and the place is full of annoying kids. They kept saying some nonsense about "Sir, this is a school" and "Sir, we're calling the police". Worst restaurant I have ever been to. Should be shut down!. 

UPDATE (25-Feb-16): On the morning of February 25th 2016, I met with the Principal and Deputy Principal of Schull Community College. Among other subjects we spoke of a Google ‚Äúreview‚Äù of Schull Community College I posted in the December of 2015. In the ‚Äúreview‚Äù I gave the school 1 star out of 5 and wrote the following, 

‚ÄúUNBELIEVABLE!. They wouldn't take my order, didn't have a table for me and the place is full of annoying kids. They kept saying some nonsense about "Sir, this is a school" and "Sir, we're calling the police". Worst restaurant I have ever been to. Should be shut down!.‚Äù.

Obviously this ‚Äúreview‚Äù is being facetious and is clearly intended as a joke. Indeed, it is difficult to see how anyone might take offence to it. However, when speaking to the Principal and Deputy Principal this morning it was demanded that I take the ‚Äúreview‚Äù down.

This is an absurd demand for various reasons. 
Firstly, I was not the only person to post a ‚Äúreview‚Äù of this type. A friend of mine and fellow student (name withheld out of respect for their privacy) wrote a similar ‚Äúreview‚Äù that also criticized the school for being a ‚Äúbad restaurant‚Äù. However, only I was asked to take my review down. This means one of two things. Either, they didn‚Äôt look at my review as if they did they would have seen his, or they did see his and decided only to ask me to take mine down.

Secondly, this violates my right to freedom of speech. Article 40.6.1 of the Irish constitution states ‚ÄúYou have a right to freely express your convictions and opinions.‚Äù. Freedom of speech is a basic human right and by being asked to take this ‚Äúreview‚Äù down I am being denied that right.

Thirdly, this is censorship. We do not let film makers take down any 1-star review of their films. Why is this any different?

Fourthly, this is flat out hypocritical. In C.S.P.E we learn of human rights (Including freedom of speech) and how we have them for a reason. In history we learn of Hitler and Mussolini and their propaganda and censorship of the media and how this was wrong.

I shall leave the ‚Äúreview‚Äù up as I have as yet not received any legal reason as to why I should take it down. When/If I have been provided with a valid legal reason as to why I must take it down, I will comply.

If you want a second chance in trying to achieve something, going to Cork College of Commerce might do just that for you, as I found out through two years there..

After not achieving what I had hoped for in my leaving certificate I was left with few education options in Cork City. I was given a courses brochure for the 2014-2015 academic year for Cork College of Commerce. 

I enrolled in their Fetac/QQI level 'Police and Security Studies' course which lasted one year. During my year there I met some great people through my course, received work experience in security, made valuable connections, received my PSA security licence and have been working in security for over a year now.  My classmates and I were received well by a  very professional set of teachers and trainers who had previous experiences in lines of work such as policing, security, crime research, and law. The college timetable was very reasonable and was given enough time to get coursework and assignment finished. They have a main study hall and computers which students can avail of. There is WIFI in most parts of the three story building as well as a smoking area, a canteen and disability supports.

After my year in Police and Security I was hungry for academia, I decided to take my chances at doing the college's 'Psychology and Social Studies' course in the aim I could use it as a back door into going onto third level education. Similarly this year I received great work experience through the college's help, was able to engage in great course content with another fantastic of teachers and learn more valuable life lessons. After being received well throughout the year and taking my confidence, the work put in during the year payed off and as I was able to take my points gathered in there onto further education. 

I am now finishing my first year of academic studies in University College Cork and still working security all thanks to my time in Cork College of Commerce.
Good staff

If you want a second chance in trying to achieve something, going to Cork College of Commerce might do just that for you, as I found out through two years there..

After not achieving what I had hoped for in my leaving certificate I was left with few education options in Cork City. I was given a courses brochure for the 2014-2015 academic year for Cork College of Commerce. 

I enrolled in their Fetac/QQI level 'Police and Security Studies' course which lasted one year. During my year there I met some great people through my course, received work experience in security, made valuable connections, received my PSA security licence and have been working in security for over a year now.  My classmates and I were received well by a  very professional set of teachers and trainers who had previous experiences in lines of work such as policing, security, crime research, and law. The college timetable was very reasonable and was given enough time to get coursework and assignment finished. They have a main study hall and computers which students can avail of. There is WIFI in most parts of the three story building as well as a smoking area, a canteen and disability supports.

After my year in Police and Security I was hungry for academia, I decided to take my chances at doing the college's 'Psychology and Social Studies' course in the aim I could use it as a back door into going onto third level education. Similarly this year I received great work experience through the college's help, was able to engage in great course content with another fantastic of teachers and learn more valuable life lessons. After being received well throughout the year and taking my confidence, the work put in during the year payed off and as I was able to take my points gathered in there onto further education. 

I am now finishing my first year of academic studies in University College Cork and still working security all thanks to my time in Cork College of Commerce.
Good staff

This school, Col√°iste na Carraige, situated close to the river Glen and the picturesque coast is involved in a student exchange with a school in Esslingen, Germany (the M√∂rike Gymnasium).

Students travel as a group and spend one week in host families of their partner schools alternately in Ireland and Germany.

Our son was participating in one of the exchanges. Later on we were curious about his stories and took the chance to visit the school, his host family and the beautiful area here in Irelands extreme north-west. 

Absolutely amazing experience: The landscape, the people, their kindness, the tranquility in this beautiful area on the western edge of Europe.

I had issues during primary school which lead to poor attendance and depression. I had very poor performance in my English skills which were often dismissed and answered with ‚Äútry harder‚Äù or ‚Äúyou‚Äôre perfectly capable‚Äù. I fail to understand why I was put forward every year despite my level, constant failure to attend and participate in school work, and obvious psychological issues induced from school. The principal of St. Mary‚Äôs National School in Edgeworthstown, Co. Longford, Helen O‚Äô Gorman, (and presumably the education board) showed little understanding and responded by having a male relative help get me to school every morning, with Helen taking over upon arrival by dragging me through the grounds and to the classroom. I would hyperventilate every time I saw that brute hag. I lost all confidence and belief in myself and quit school at the age of twelve with my depression, reclusiveness, and suicidal thoughts getting progressively worse.

I had a lot of people put immense pressure on me to get involved in education and I made it clear that I would only agree to homeschooling. Home tuition was eventually arranged with a woman named Monica Coyle. She explained that I was to do home tuition for a short period and then go back to school. I was unhappy with such an arrangement and made it clear that I would not go back into a school environment. Nasty Monica showed no understanding whatsoever and talked down to me as if I was just a difficult oblivious child. She also supposedly conveyed inaccurate information about me to others (e.g. claiming that I liked routine despite being chaotic and unorganized, labeling me as autistic) which could not have been derived from our interactions.

I eventually agreed due to pressure to do home tuition and go back to school on the condition that someone more suitable be found. It was arranged with a man who seemed more respectful but the tuition didn‚Äôt last long. I eventually tried enrolling in a school in Longford, Templemichael College (again due to the pressure put on me), however, the principal was horrendous. She would say scornful things like ‚Äúlife does not stop and start at your convenience‚Äù and ask me why I think the school would want to accept me, with contempt. She also criticised my posture, difficulty making eye contact, hair length, hygiene, and lifestyle etc. She even sneered when I proposed that I wanted an education and to be a father some day (no longer a pursuit). She seemed to believe I would not make a good father. After this distressful incident I came out in dozens of hives and ulcers and my condition worsened, as I began heavily abusing solvents and attempted hanging myself (obviously botched that). 

At the age of sixteen I was again pressured into education (by an incompetent psychiatrist named Con McDonagh). I did so to please them after being discharged from an ‚Äúadult-only‚Äù psychiatric unit (while an adolescent) where the treatment was degrading (e.g. not being allowed to use a toilet alone and restrained as punitive measures for being argumentative) and counter-therapeutic (e.g. the administration of a drug which causes weight gain to a patient with anorexia nervosa). I was initially left with the impression that I would not have to attend mainstream classes and would receive all of my education from within a unit on the grounds of Ballymahon Vocational School, however, within a short period after attending I was informed that the plan was that I would join mainstream classes when ready, which is something I was not capable of doing neither academically nor psychologically. Although my presence at Ballymahon Vocational School proved fruitless (initiated to please the health services) I can only praise the majority of their staff. There were some very nice people working there. Most were not scornful nor belittling towards vulnerable students. Also, the other students I had observed and the few I had interacted with here seemed quite pleased. I would recommend this school over any other in Longford. There's quite a few awful schools so be careful choosing!
